[1] India - Delhi
Date: Sat 11 Mar 2006
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: NDTV.com [edited]
<http://www.ndtv.com/template/template.asp?
template=Health&slug=Brain+fever+kills+21+in+Delhi&id=18941&callid=0&category=N
ational>

Brain fever kills 21 in Delhi
-----------------------------
At least 21 people are dead, while 370 others are believed to be
affected by meningococcemia, the highly infectious brain fever that
has gripped Delhi.
While the government is trying to combat its spread through
antibiotics, medicines are not reaching affected areas quickly enough.
The meningococcus spreads through contact. The 1st step in containing
the disease is chemoprophylaxis with antimicrobials, which should be
given to the patient's family. This is followed by immunization of
the population in affected areas.
"Chemoprophylaxis is being done, and we are doing house to house
surveys. Health workers are vaccinated," said Dr. KK Tiwari, Director
of Health Services, MCD.
Though the government is banking on this strategy, the situation on
the ground is very different. In a densely populated and congested
area in Karol Bagh, 70 people have been diagnosed with brain fever,
and the deaths have begun. Infection breeds easily in these areas,
with several people, most of them migrant laborers, sharing a small
living space. Workers on the ground say that, in most cases, they
cannot track down a patient's family. Clearly, the scale of infection
seems much higher than reported.
[Byline: Priyam Bhasin]
