[2] Burkina Faso, Niger
Date: Sat 11 Mar 2006
From: Pablo Nart <pablo.nart@terra.es>
Source: AllAfrica.com [edited]
<http://allafrica.com/stories/200603100699.html>

Hundreds of people have been reported dead from meningitis in West Africa in
the last few weeks.
Worst hit has been Burkina Faso, where 246 people have died,
according to the medical aid group Medecins Sans Frontieres, and over
2000 more have fallen ill from the meningitis bacterium (_Neisseria
meningitidis_), which attacks the brain and spinal chord.
Across Burkina Faso's northern border, 44 people died, and 614 people were
reported ill between 1 Jan & 27 Feb 2006 in Niger, according to the National
Health Information System, SNIS. And to the south, in war-divided Cote
d'Ivoire, the UN children's agency UNICEF has reported 94 cases and 33 deaths
from meningitis.
Meningitis is endemic in much of the arid Sahel region of West
Africa, with outbreaks most common during the dry season, from
January to March.
The Burkina Faso government plans a major vaccination campaign in the
10 epidemic-hit districts that lie in the west, southwest and north
of the country, according to Souleyman Sanou, who is heading the
government's campaign against the illness.
"The government has bought 1 million doses of [vaccine], which will
be given to the population free of charge," said Sanou, who added
that 2 million more doses were being sought.
However, the director of communications in the ministry of health,
Rene Sebgo, said further tests would have to be carried out to
determine the strain of meningitis.
In 2002, an outbreak of the W135 strain of meningitis afflicted 13 000 people
and killed 1500, according to the WHO. Many of the cheaper vaccines long used
against meningitis are less effective against the W135 strain, according to
WHO.
Government officials are worried that a week long cultural festival
due to begin in the country's 2nd city, Bobo-Dioulasso, which lies in
the heart of the meningitis outbreak area, could assist in the spread
of the disease. The thousands of artists and attendees due to flock
to the biannual event that begins on 26 Mar 2006 have been advised to
get shots 8 to 10 days before travel.
In Niger, the most badly hit area is Maradi, some 650 km east of
Niamey, where 31 have died and 514 have been registered with
meningitis, SNIS said.
The government has dispatched 30 000 doses of vaccine as well as
medicine for more than 900 patients, while Medecins Sans Frontieres
has promised 710 000 vaccinations, half of them being already in hand.
But the Health Ministry says Niger needs 3 million doses of vaccine
as well as enough drugs and syringes to deal with an expected 25 000
cases.
--
Pablo Nart
<pablo.nart@terra.es>
